Headline::::
Sweet, murderous robins




DateTime::::2016-03-10T05:30:08+0000



<p><span class="drop-cap"><span class="drop-cap__inner">A</span></span> fevered burst of birdsong drew more than one pair of eyes to the branch of a hedgerow tree. Fraught with seasonal urgency, the <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://sounds.bl.uk/Environment/British-wildlife-recordings/022M-W1CDR0001376-1100V0">robin’s song</a> was a liquid stream; not a gentle brook, but a gushing beck, some notes thrown high and uncontrollably as if dashed against a rock, others pitched down a waterfall, and all poured out in a tumbling, erratic, attention-seeking rush.</p>

<p>There was a pause. Another <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.garden-birds.co.uk/birds/robin.htm">robin</a> worked its way down the hedge towards it, then alighted on a near parallel perch about a metre away. The first bird threw out its chest, arched its back so that its head all but touched its shoulders and began to rear up and down in poised sweeps, a series of movements that – in human terms – would not look out of place on a yoga mat.</p>

<p>The scene was backlit by a low sun, so there were no distractions of colour and tone. All of my focus was on the physicality of stylised gestures that would have been clearly read and understood by the bird on the next branch.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/nov/26/country-diary-sandy-bedfordshire-niemann-mistle-thrush-mistletoe-birch-late-autumn">Nature’s stormcock on mistletoe duty</a> </p>

<p>We walked on beyond where the hedge ran out and along the track whose bordering ditches led up to a wood recorded in the <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/feb/10/1">Domesday Book</a>. Yellows captured the corner of my eye; the first flush of dandelions, but also flowering <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.countrysideinfo.co.uk/primrose.htm">primroses</a>, relics of hedges past. Some were flat rosettes of leaves and unfurling stems that promised more to come.</p>

<p>A patch of <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.woodlands.co.uk/blog/flora-and-fauna/dogs-mercury/">dog’s mercury</a> held to a grass slope that had been scraped last winter to bare earth. These plants were raising their annual heads early and would subside before the blade of a summer tractor could bring them low.</p>

<p>At the wood’s edge, with its array of Private: Keep Out signs, we swivelled and returned downhill. When we reached the same spot in the hedge as before, the robins had progressed to a flying tandem, processing from tree to tree, perch to perch.</p>

<p>Should one bird catch the other, it would surely try to bash its little brains out. Sweet robins, with their sweet song and their <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.bto.org/volunteer-surveys/gbw/gardens-wildlife/garden-birds/a-z-garden-birds/robin">murderous intent</a>.</p>

<p><span class="bullet">•</span> Follow <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://twitter.com/gdncountrydiary">Country Diary</a> on Twitter</p>




