The tradition is that a robin tried to remove the crown of thorns from Jesus' head (as he was being crucified) to lessen Jesus' pain. In doing so, it injured itself and all robins since then have been coloured red to remind us of that robin's brave and selfless attempt, ca. 30 CE.



Author::::nonNTT
DateTime::::2016-03-10T12:53:36Z
In his classic monograph, The Life of the Robin (1943), David Lack came across only eight cases of serious fighting between rival males during his four years of intensive study. Almost all the conflicts were harmless ‘bluff fights’. An exception was when one bird lost a lot of head feathers and started to succumb. It survived by retreating and giving up its territory and mate to the intruder.Lack concludes that, despite several recorded cases of fights to the death in the literature, such events are extremely rare.It is also important to recognise that the vast majority of territorial disputes are resolved by a ‘natural diplomacy’ using competitions of song and display, with never a claw or beak clashing in anger



